Western leaders have said the meeting between Amani National Congress leader Musalia Mudavadi (pictured) and his Ford Kenya counterpart Moses Wetang&rsquo;ula on Monday is evidence of a solidifying opposition.Kakamega Senator Boni Khalwale said the meeting created a ray of hope about the much-sought unity of leaders as it has proven wrong those committed to ensuring Western leaders do not work together.&ldquo;The meeting has sent a signal that our people can unite just like the rest of Kenyans and need the respect they deserve,&rdquo; Khalwale said. He said Ford Kenya wants Wetang&rsquo;ula picked as the opposition flagbearer.Khalwale, however, said Ford Kenya will support Mudavadi if he is picked as the torchbearer. The two were paraded by Vihiga Senator George Khaniri at Bomas of Kenya during the launch of NASA and promised to remain united. They met at a Karen club, signaling a start by the opposition to work in unity ahead of the election. Sources close to the two told the Star the meeting was part of the confidence building and bonding within NASA.The sources said the meeting was meant to dispel the notion that NASA is pulling in different directions in Western.&ldquo;They committed to working together, starting with holding joint voter registration mobilisation rallies starting in Vihiga this Saturday,&rdquo; the source said. The two met on a day when Deputy President William Ruto encountered resistance in Bungoma after youth barricaded his way, forcing him to change route. Lurambi MP Raphael Otaalo said close working links between Mudavadi and Wetang&rsquo;ula are good for the opposition. &ldquo;The resistance met by the DP in Bungoma shows time is up for those thriving on Luhya disunity,&rdquo; he said.